"'''Some Kind-A Earthquake'''" is a song written by [[Duane Eddy]] and [[Lee Hazlewood]] and performed by Eddy. The song reached #12 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and #37 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in 1959.<ref>[http://www.musicvf.com/song.php?title=Some+Kind-a+Earthquake+by+Duane+Eddy&id=13103 Duane Eddy, "Some Kind-A Earthquake" Chart Positions] Retrieved April 26, 2014</ref> The song appeared on his 1960 album, ''$1,000,000.00 Worth of Twang''.<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Duane-Eddy-His-Twangy-Guitar-The-Rebels-100000000-Worth-Of-Twang/release/2887896 Duane Eddy, ''$1,000,000.00 Worth of Twang''] Retrieved April 26, 2014</ref>

The single's [[A-Side and B-Side|B-side]], "First Love, First Tears", reached #59 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>[http://www.musicvf.com/song.php?title=First+Love%2C+First+Tears+by+Duane+Eddy&id=13102 Duane Eddy, "First Love, First Tears" Chart Positions] Retrieved April 26, 2014</ref>

The song was produced by [[Lee Hazlewood]] and [[Lester Sill]].<ref>[http://www.45cat.com/record/1130us2 Duane Eddy, "Some Kind-A Earthquake" single release] Retrieved April 26, 2014</ref>

At 1:17, it is the shortest song to have ever hit the ''Billboard'' Top 40, or indeed the Top 75.<ref>Trust, Gary; [https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7549893/longest-shortest-hot-100-hits-kendrick-lamar-beyonce ‘The Longest & Shortest Hot 100 Hits: From Kendrick Lamar, Beyonce & David Bowie to Piko-Taro’]</ref>

